To improve both the performance and adaptability of the code, as well as to drastically reduce the complexity and character count, we can leverage C++'s standard library. 

The original code is a basic, non-optimized Quicksort which can lead to O(n²) worst-case behavior (e.g. on already sorted arrays) and stack overflows due to deep recursion. 

By utilizing `std::sort`, we instantly transition to a highly optimized Introsort algorithm (a hybrid of Quicksort, Heapsort, and Insertion Sort). It provides:
1. **O(n log n) worst-case time complexity** avoiding the quicksort worst-case pitfall.
2. Better constant factors and locality of reference.
3. Built-in adaptability as it switches algorithms under the hood based on partition depth and subarray sizes.
4. A dramatically simplified and shorter codebase.

